  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects of AML regulations typically include:\n\n1. Requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Monitor and report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\n2. Major regulatory frameworks include:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States\n- European Union AML Directives\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) international standards\n\n3. Regulated entities include:\n- Banks\n- Credit unions\n- Investment firms\n- Money transfer services\n- Cryptocurrency exchanges\n\nThese regulations aim to detect and prevent financial crimes like money laundering, terrorist financing, and other illicit financial activities.",
